I very much hope that PBS finds the money to keep this site alive. I started this thread, and it's a profound moving experience reading it because it explores every aspect of the war and the Vietnam era. It's encapsules all of the raw emotion of the time that is still with us today. It's a microcosm of the country. It's a living history. I wish I could print it off to show other people, and to save it for posterity, but since the type is white on black, it won't print.<br><br>
I would like to thank Chris for the kind words he said about my posts. I suggest everyone read the article &quot;The Sky's the Limit&quot; on page 52 of the latest, March 24, 1997 issue of TIME magazine. It describes how even today, after the Cold War, the American military spends enormous amounts of money on an enormous number of extremely expensive lethal weapons which they then flood the world with, and are frequently used by both sides in dozens of conflicts all over the world. Despite the fact that Iran derided both superpowers as &quot;The Great Satan&quot;, that didn't prevent them from buying weapons from both superpowers. Both superpowers sold weapons to both sides in the Iran-Iraq War. At one point, the United States tried to get Saddam to buy more U.S. weapons hoping that would make Iraq more successful in the war, hoping that would cause Iran to buy more U.S. weapons. The United States flooded Afganistan with weapons which they continue to use against each other today. The United States flooded Somalia with weapons which they not only used against each other but against us also.
